'''Rara Avis''' is an [[ghost town]] located in [[Itawamba County, Mississippi]], approximately {{convert|0.5|mi|km|1}} west of the [[Alabama]] state line.

Rara Avis was settled in 1850,<ref name="GNIS"/> and the town name translated to Latin means "rare bird".

The population was 100 in 1900.<ref name="Rowland">{{cite book | last = Rowland | first = Dunbar | title = Mississippi: Comprising Sketches of Counties, Towns, Events, Institutions, and Persons, Arranged in Cyclopedic Form | publisher = Southern Historical Publishing Association | year = 1907 | url = https://dcms.lds.org/delivery/DeliveryManagerServlet?dps_pid=IE97852 | volume = 2 | page = 519}}</ref>  A post office was established in 1902.<ref>{{cite web | title = Mississippi: Dates that First Rural Routes Were Established at Post Offices, through 1904 | publisher = United States Postal Service | date = April 2008 | url = http://about.usps.com/who-we-are/postal-history/first-rfd-mississippi.pdf}}</ref>

Author and Baptist minister James Garvin Chastain Sr., was born in Rara Avis in 1853.<ref>{{cite book | last = Lloyd | first = James B. | title = Lives of Mississippi Authors, 1817-1967 | publisher = University Press of Mississippi | year = 2009 | url = http://books.google.ca/books?id=RfXGJBB1HvoC&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false | page = 86}}</ref>

The post office closed and the hamlet ceased to exist in 1926.{{cn|date=April 2014}}

